    {
      "id": "topic35-lo-1",
      "front": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; opacity: 0.85; margin-bottom: 10px; font-weight: 500;\">Learning Objective</div><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.5;\">Compare the cardiac and the skeletal muscle with respect to: fiber size, electrical connections between cells, and arrangement of myofilaments. Based on ion permeability and electrical resistance describe the role of gap junctions in creating a functional syncytium.</div></div>"
      },
      "back": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700;\">Cardiac vs Skeletal Muscle Comparison</div></div><div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dbeafe 0%, #eff6ff 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Cardiac Muscle</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 8px;\"><strong>Fiber Size:</strong></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px; padding-left: 8px;\">• Diameter: <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">10-20 μm</span><br>• Length: <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">100-150 μm</span><br>• <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">Branched</span> fibers<br>• <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">One central nucleus</span></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 8px;\"><strong>Electrical Connections:</strong></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px; padding-left: 8px;\">• <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">Intercalated discs</span><br>• Gap junctions + desmosomes<br>• <span style=\"background: #f0fdf4; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #166534; font-weight: 600;\">Electrically connected</span></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 8px;\"><strong>Myofilaments:</strong></div><div style=\"padding-left: 8px;\">• Striated appearance<br>• Parallel sarcomeres (~2 μm)<br>• Actin & myosin organized</div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef2f2 0%, #fef2f2 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; color: #dc2626; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Skeletal Muscle</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 8px;\"><strong>Fiber Size:</strong></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px; padding-left: 8px;\">• Diameter: <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">40-100 μm</span><br>• Length: <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">up to 20 cm</span><br>• <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">Unbranched</span> cylindrical<br>• <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">Many peripheral nuclei</span></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 8px;\"><strong>Electrical Connections:</strong></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px; padding-left: 8px;\">• <span style=\"background: #fef2f2; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">No electrical connections</span><br>• Electrically isolated<br>• Individual motor neuron innervation</div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 8px;\"><strong>Myofilaments:</strong></div><div style=\"padding-left: 8px;\">• Striated appearance<br>• Parallel sarcomeres (longer)<br>• More uniform arrangement</div></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700;\">Gap Junctions: Creating a Functional Syncytium</div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f0fdf4 0%, #f0fdf4 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #166534; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Structure</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Made of <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">connexons</span> (protein complexes)<br>• Each connexon = <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">6 connexin subunits</span><br>• Create <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">2 nm channels</span> between adjacent cells</div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #eff6ff 0%, #eff6ff 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 10px;\">High Ion Permeability</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Allows <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">rapid movement</span> of ions:<br>  &nbsp;&nbsp;→ Na⁺, Ca²⁺, K⁺<br>• Ions pass <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">directly between cells</span><br>• Facilitates <span style=\"background: #dbeafe; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #1e3a5f; font-weight: 600;\">action potential propagation</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fefce8 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #ca8a04; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Low Electrical Resistance</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Provides <span style=\"color: #ca8a04; font-weight: 600;\">low-resistance pathway</span> for current flow<br>• Enables <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">rapid electrical signal spread</span><br>• All connected cells <span style=\"background: #fefce8; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #92400e; font-weight: 600;\">depolarize almost simultaneously</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f3e8ff 0%, #f3e8ff 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #7c3aed;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Functional Syncytium Result</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">Longitudinal conduction very fast</span> (end-to-end junctions)<br>• No transversal gap junctions<br>• Entire <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">atrial mass</span> contracts as <span style=\"background: #f3e8ff; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #6b21a8; font-weight: 600;\">one unit</span><br>• Entire <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">ventricular mass</span> contracts as <span style=\"background: #f3e8ff; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #6b21a8; font-weight: 600;\">one unit</span><br>• <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">Despite being individual cells!</span></div></div>"
      },
      "tags": ["cardiac-muscle", "structure", "gap-junctions", "syncytium", "high-yield"]
    },
    {
      "id": "topic35-lo-2",
      "front": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; opacity: 0.85; margin-bottom: 10px; font-weight: 500;\">Learning Objective</div><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.5;\">Contrast the duration of the action potential and the refractory period in a cardiac muscle and skeletal muscle. Sketch the temporal relationship between an action potential and the resulting contraction (twitch) in a cardiac muscle cell and in a skeletal muscle fiber. Based on this graph, explain why cardiac muscle cannot remain in a state of sustained (tetanic) contraction.</div></div>"
      },
      "back": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700;\">Action Potential & Refractory Period Comparison</div></div><div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dbeafe 0%, #eff6ff 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Cardiac Muscle</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px;\"><strong>Action Potential Duration:</strong><br><span style=\"font-size: 1.3rem; color: #2563eb; font-weight: 700;\">200-300 ms</span></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px;\"><strong>Why so long?</strong><br>• <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">Plateau phase</span><br>• L-type Ca²⁺ channels<br>• Prolonged depolarization</div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px;\"><strong>Refractory Period:</strong><br><span style=\"font-size: 1.2rem; color: #059669; font-weight: 700;\">200-300 ms</span><br><span style=\"background: #f0fdf4; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #166534; font-size: 0.85rem;\">Nearly matches AP duration</span></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef2f2 0%, #fef2f2 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; color: #dc2626; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Skeletal Muscle</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px;\"><strong>Action Potential Duration:</strong><br><span style=\"font-size: 1.3rem; color: #dc2626; font-weight: 700;\">1-2 ms</span></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px;\"><strong>Why so brief?</strong><br>• <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">No plateau phase</span><br>• Rapid depolarization<br>• Rapid repolarization</div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 12px;\"><strong>Refractory Period:</strong><br><span style=\"font-size: 1.2rem; color: #dc2626; font-weight: 700;\">1-2 ms</span><br><span style=\"background: #fef2f2; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #991b1b; font-size: 0.85rem;\">Much shorter!</span></div></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700;\">Temporal Relationship: AP vs Contraction</div></div><div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"background: #eff6ff; padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 10px; text-align: center;\">Cardiac Muscle Graph</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"background: white; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 10px; text-align: center;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6b7280; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Action Potential</div><div style=\"background: #2563eb; height: 40px; border-radius: 4px; position: relative;\"><div style=\"position: absolute; top: 50%; left: 50%; transform: translate(-50%, -50%); color: white; font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 600;\">200-300 ms</div></div><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6b7280; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Mechanical Contraction</div><div style=\"background: #059669; height: 50px; border-radius: 4px;\"></div><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6b7280; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Refractory Period</div><div style=\"background: #7c3aed; height: 35px; border-radius: 4px;\"></div></div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; color: #1e3a5f; font-weight: 600; text-align: center;\">AP & contraction OVERLAP<br><span style=\"background: #dbeafe; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; margin-top: 4px; display: inline-block;\">Refractory period extends through entire contraction</span></div></div></div><div style=\"background: #fef2f2; padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #dc2626; margin-bottom: 10px; text-align: center;\">Skeletal Muscle Graph</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"background: white; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 10px; text-align: center;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6b7280; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Action Potential</div><div style=\"background: #dc2626; height: 15px; width: 20%; border-radius: 4px; margin-bottom: 6px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.75rem; color: white; padding: 1px;\">1-2 ms</div></div><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6b7280; margin-top: 10px; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Mechanical Contraction</div><div style=\"background: #059669; height: 50px; border-radius: 4px; margin-bottom: 6px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; color: white; padding: 16px 0; text-align: center;\">Much longer</div></div><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; color: #6b7280; margin-top: 4px; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Refractory Period</div><div style=\"background: #7c3aed; height: 15px; width: 20%; border-radius: 4px;\"></div></div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; color: #991b1b; font-weight: 600; text-align: center;\">Brief AP precedes contraction<br><span style=\"background: #fef2f2; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; margin-top: 4px; display: inline-block;\">Refractory period ends BEFORE relaxation</span></div></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef2f2 0%, #fee2e2 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; color: #991b1b; margin-bottom: 10px;\">⚠️ Why Cardiac Muscle CANNOT Tetanize</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\"><span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 700;\">Prolonged refractory period overlapping with contraction</span> prevents re-excitation</div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\">• Cannot fire another action potential until current contraction + relaxation cycle completes</div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\">• Cell is <span style=\"background: #fef2f2; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #991b1b; font-weight: 600;\">absolutely refractory</span> during entire contraction</div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fefce8 0%, #fef3c7 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #ca8a04;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Clinical Significance</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\"><strong>Essential for heart function:</strong></div><div style=\"padding-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">1. Heart must <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">contract</span> to eject blood<br>2. Heart must <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">relax</span> to fill with blood<br>3. <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">Both phases are mandatory!</span></div><div style=\"background: #7f1d1d; color: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px; margin-top: 10px;\"><strong>If cardiac muscle could tetanize:</strong><br>→ Heart would remain <span style=\"font-weight: 700;\">CONTRACTED</span><br>→ No filling with blood<br>→ No blood flow<br>→ <span style=\"background: #991b1b; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; font-weight: 700;\">LIFE-THREATENING</span></div></div></div>"
      },
      "tags": ["cardiac-muscle", "action-potential", "refractory-period", "tetanus", "high-yield"]
    },
    {
      "id": "topic35-lo-3",
      "front": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; opacity: 0.85; margin-bottom: 10px; font-weight: 500;\">Learning Objective</div><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.5;\">State the steps in excitation-contraction coupling in cardiac muscle. Outline the sequence of events that occurs between the initiation of an action potential in a cardiac muscle cell, the resulting contraction and then relaxation of that cell. Provide specific details about the source of intracellular Ca²⁺ increase and the special role of Ca²⁺ in the modulation of contraction force and relaxation of cardiac muscle.</div></div>"
      },
      "back": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700;\">Excitation-Contraction Coupling Steps</div></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f0fdf4 0%, #dcfce7 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #059669; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 1: Action Potential Generation</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Action potential initiated in <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">sarcolemma</span><br>• Spreads rapidly across entire cell membrane</div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #eff6ff 0%, #dbeafe 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 2: L-type Ca²⁺ Channel Opening</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Depolarization opens <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">L-type (long-lasting)</span> voltage-gated Ca²⁺ channels<br>• Located in sarcolemma & T-tubules<br>• <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">Extracellular Ca²⁺</span> enters during plateau phase<br>• <span style=\"background: #dbeafe; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #1e3a5f; font-size: 0.85rem;\">Small but critical influx</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f3e8ff 0%, #e9d5ff 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 3: Calcium-Induced Calcium Release (CICR)</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Small Ca²⁺ influx stimulates <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">ryanodine receptors (RyR)</span><br>• RyR located on <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">sarcoplasmic reticulum (SR)</span> membrane<br>• Causes <span style=\"background: #f3e8ff; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #6b21a8; font-weight: 600;\">LARGE Ca²⁺ release</span> from SR into cytoplasm<br>• <span style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-style: italic;\">Amplification mechanism!</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #ca8a04; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 4: Intracellular Ca²⁺ Increase</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Combined Ca²⁺ from both sources:<br>  &nbsp;&nbsp;→ Extracellular (via L-type channels)<br>  &nbsp;&nbsp;→ SR stores (via CICR)<br>• Significantly increases <span style=\"color: #ca8a04; font-weight: 600;\">cytoplasmic [Ca²⁺]</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #eff6ff 0%, #dbeafe 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 5: Troponin Binding</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Ca²⁺ binds <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">troponin C</span> on actin filaments<br>• Causes <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">conformational change</span> in troponin complex<br>• Shifts <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">tropomyosin</span> away from myosin-binding sites<br>• <span style=\"background: #dbeafe; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #1e3a5f;\">Binding sites now EXPOSED</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f0fdf4 0%, #dcfce7 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #059669; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 6-7: Cross-Bridge Cycling & Contraction</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Myosin heads bind actin → <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">cross-bridge formation</span><br>• Power stroke (myosin pulls actin)<br>• ATP hydrolysis provides energy<br>• Myosin detaches and resets<br>• Cycle repeats → <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">CONTRACTION & FORCE</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef2f2 0%, #fecaca 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #991b1b; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 8: Ca²⁺ Removal (Relaxation Begins)</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><strong>Three pathways remove Ca²⁺:</strong><br><div style=\"padding-left: 8px; margin-top: 6px;\">1. <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">SERCA pump</span> → transports Ca²⁺ back into SR<br>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<span style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-style: italic;\">(main pathway, regulated by phospholamban)</span><br>2. <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">Na⁺/Ca²⁺ exchanger (NCX)</span> → extrudes Ca²⁺ from cell<br>3. <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">Sarcolemma Ca²⁺-ATPase</span> → pumps Ca²⁺ out (minor)</div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #e0e7ff 0%, #c7d2fe 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #4338ca; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 9-10: Decreased Ca²⁺ & Relaxation</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Cytoplasmic [Ca²⁺] decreases<br>• Ca²⁺ dissociates from troponin C<br>• Tropomyosin <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">re-blocks</span> myosin-binding sites on actin<br>• Cross-bridge cycling halts<br>• Muscle returns to <span style=\"color: #4338ca; font-weight: 600;\">resting state</span> → <span style=\"background: #e0e7ff; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #3730a3; font-weight: 600;\">RELAXATION</span></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700;\">Sources of Intracellular Ca²⁺ Increase</div></div><div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #eff6ff 0%, #dbeafe 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Source 1: Extracellular Ca²⁺</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Enters via <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">L-type Ca²⁺ channels</span><br>• During action potential plateau<br>• <span style=\"background: #dbeafe; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #1e3a5f; font-size: 0.85rem;\">Small amount</span><br>• <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">Critical trigger!</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f3e8ff 0%, #e9d5ff 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #7c3aed;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Source 2: SR Ca²⁺ Stores</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Released via <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">ryanodine receptors</span><br>• Triggered by extracellular Ca²⁺ (CICR)<br>• <span style=\"background: #f3e8ff; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #6b21a8; font-size: 0.85rem;\">LARGE amount</span><br>• <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">Main contraction driver!</span></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700;\">Special Role of Ca²⁺ in Force & Relaxation Modulation</div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dcfce7 0%, #bbf7d0 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #166534; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Ca²⁺ Modulates Contraction Force</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\"><strong>More Ca²⁺ = Stronger Contraction</strong></div><div style=\"padding-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">• Ca²⁺ amount <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">directly determines</span> # of active cross-bridges<br>• Higher [Ca²⁺] → more troponin C binding<br>• More binding sites exposed<br>• <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">Greater contractile force</span></div><div style=\"background: #f0fdf4; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px; margin-top: 10px;\"><strong style=\"color: #166534;\">Sympathetic Stimulation (Positive Inotropy):</strong><br>• Enhances Ca²⁺ influx through L-type channels<br>• Stimulates SR Ca²⁺ release<br>• β-adrenergic signaling + PKA phosphorylation<br>→ <span style=\"background: #dcfce7; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #14532d; font-weight: 600;\">Stronger contraction!</span></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dbeafe 0%, #bfdbfe 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #1e40af; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Ca²⁺ Modulates Relaxation (Lusitropy)</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 10px;\"><strong>SERCA Pump Regulation:</strong></div><div style=\"padding-left: 8px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">• <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">Phospholamban</span> normally <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">inhibits</span> SERCA<br>• When unphosphorylated → slow Ca²⁺ reuptake<br>• When phosphorylated → fast Ca²⁺ reuptake</div><div style=\"background: #eff6ff; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px; margin-top: 10px;\"><strong style=\"color: #1e40af;\">Sympathetic Stimulation (Positive Lusitropy):</strong><br>• Phosphorylates phospholamban (via PKA)<br>• Removes SERCA inhibition<br>• <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">Accelerates Ca²⁺ reuptake</span> into SR<br>→ <span style=\"background: #dbeafe; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #1e3a5f; font-weight: 600;\">Faster relaxation!</span></div></div></div>"
      },
      "tags": ["cardiac-muscle", "excitation-contraction", "calcium", "CICR", "high-yield"]
