      "id": "topic35-lo-4",
      "front": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; opacity: 0.85; margin-bottom: 10px; font-weight: 500;\">Learning Objective</div><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.5;\">How do the following factors increase the power of contraction (positive inotropy) in the cardiac muscle: increasing the length of muscle fibres (heterometric control), partial inhibition of the Na⁺-K⁺-ATPase and increasing the extracellular Ca²⁺?</div></div>"
      },
      "back": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700;\">Three Mechanisms of Positive Inotropy</div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dcfce7 0%, #bbf7d0 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; color: #166534; margin-bottom: 12px;\">1. Increasing Muscle Fiber Length (Heterometric Control)</div><div style=\"background: #f0fdf4; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #059669; margin-bottom: 8px;\">Frank-Starling Mechanism</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Increased <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">end-diastolic volume</span> (EDV)<br>• Stretches cardiac muscle fibers<br>• <span style=\"background: #dcfce7; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #14532d; font-weight: 600;\">More stretch = Stronger contraction</span></div></div><div style=\"background: white; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 8px;\">Optimal Sarcomere Length</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Stretching brings sarcomeres to <span style=\"font-size: 1.1rem; color: #2563eb; font-weight: 700;\">~2.2 μm</span><br>• <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">Ideal actin-myosin overlap</span><br>• Maximum cross-bridge formation possible<br>• More cross-bridges = <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">greater force</span></div></div><div style=\"background: #eff6ff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 8px;\">Increased Ca²⁺ Sensitivity</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Stretching increases <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">troponin C sensitivity</span> to Ca²⁺<br>• <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">Same [Ca²⁺]</span> → <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">stronger contraction</span><br>• May also improve SR Ca²⁺ uptake/release</div></div><div style=\"background: #fefce8; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e;\">Clinical: Frank-Starling Law</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.5; color: #1e293b;\">\"Force of contraction ∝ initial fiber length\"<br>→ Heart matches <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">output to input</span><br>→ More venous return = stronger beat</div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dbeafe 0%, #bfdbfe 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; color: #1e40af; margin-bottom: 12px;\">2. Partial Inhibition of Na⁺-K⁺-ATPase</div><div style=\"background: #eff6ff; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 8px;\">Normal Na⁺-K⁺-ATPase Function</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Pumps <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">3 Na⁺ OUT</span> of cell<br>• Pumps <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">2 K⁺ IN</span> to cell<br>• Maintains electrochemical gradients</div></div><div style=\"background: white; padding: 14px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Effect of Partial Inhibition (Cardiac Glycosides)</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><div style=\"margin-bottom: 8px;\"><span style=\"background: #fef3c7; padding: 4px 8px; border-radius: 4px; font-weight: 600;\">Example: Digoxin</span></div><div style=\"padding: 12px; background: #f3f4f6; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 10px;\"><div style=\"font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Step 1: Na⁺ Accumulation</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 10px;\">• Less Na⁺ pumped out<br>• Intracellular [Na⁺] <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">increases ↑</span></div><div style=\"font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Step 2: NCX Activity Reduced</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 10px;\">• <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">Na⁺/Ca²⁺ exchanger (NCX)</span> normally extrudes Ca²⁺<br>• Uses Na⁺ gradient to pump Ca²⁺ out<br>• High [Na⁺] inside → <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">reduced NCX activity</span></div><div style=\"font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Step 3: Ca²⁺ Accumulation</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 10px;\">• Less Ca²⁺ removal from cell<br>• Intracellular [Ca²⁺] <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">increases ↑</span><br>• More Ca²⁺ stored in SR</div><div style=\"font-weight: 600; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Step 4: Enhanced Contraction</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem;\">• Subsequent depolarizations → <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">more SR Ca²⁺ release</span><br>• More troponin C binding<br>• <span style=\"background: #dcfce7; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #14532d; font-weight: 600;\">Increased contractile force!</span></div></div></div></div><div style=\"background: #fef3c7; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e;\">Clinical Use</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.5; color: #1e293b;\">Cardiac glycosides treat <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">congestive heart failure</span><br>→ Counteracts negative inotropy<br>→ Improves contractility when heart is weak</div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #ca8a04;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e; margin-bottom: 12px;\">3. Increasing Extracellular Ca²⁺</div><div style=\"background: #fefce8; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #ca8a04; margin-bottom: 8px;\">Mechanism</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Higher extracellular [Ca²⁺]<br>• <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">Greater Ca²⁺ influx</span> through L-type channels<br>• During action potential depolarization<br>• <span style=\"background: #fef3c7; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #78350f; font-weight: 600;\">More trigger Ca²⁺ available</span></div></div><div style=\"background: white; padding: 12px; border-radius: 6px; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 8px;\">CICR Amplification</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• More Ca²⁺ entry → <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">more CICR</span> from SR<br>• Greater total intracellular [Ca²⁺]<br>• More troponin C binding<br>• More cross-bridges form<br>• <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">Greater contractile force</span></div></div><div style=\"background: #eff6ff; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; font-weight: 700; color: #1e40af; margin-bottom: 6px;\">Type: Homeometric (Ca²⁺-dependent)</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.9rem; line-height: 1.5; color: #1e293b;\"><strong>Seen in:</strong><br>• Sympathetic stimulation (physiological)<br>• Hypercalcemia (pathological)</div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #e0e7ff 0%, #c7d2fe 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; margin-top: 16px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #4338ca; margin-bottom: 10px; text-align: center;\">Summary: Three Paths to Positive Inotropy</div><div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr 1fr; gap: 10px; font-size: 0.9rem;\"><div style=\"background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px; text-align: center;\"><div style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 4px;\">↑ Fiber Length</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem;\">Optimal sarcomere overlap</div></div><div style=\"background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px; text-align: center;\"><div style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 4px;\">↓ Na⁺-K⁺-ATPase</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem;\">↑ [Ca²⁺] via NCX inhibition</div></div><div style=\"background: white; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px; text-align: center;\"><div style=\"color: #ca8a04; font-weight: 700; margin-bottom: 4px;\">↑ Extracellular Ca²⁺</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem;\">↑ CICR amplification</div></div></div></div>"
      },
      "tags": ["cardiac-muscle", "inotropy", "frank-starling", "calcium", "high-yield"]
