      "id": "topic35-lo-5",
      "front": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 16px 20px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.7rem; text-transform: uppercase; letter-spacing: 0.1em; opacity: 0.85; margin-bottom: 10px; font-weight: 500;\">Learning Objective</div><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 600; line-height: 1.5;\">Explain the positive lusitropic effect induced by stimulation of the adrenergic receptors?</div></div>"
      },
      "back": {
        "text": "<div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin: -8px -8px 16px -8px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.1rem; font-weight: 700;\">Positive Lusitropic Effect (Faster Relaxation)</div></div><div style=\"background: #eff6ff; padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 10px;\">What is Positive Lusitropy?</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><strong>Definition:</strong> <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">Increased rate of cardiac muscle relaxation</span></div><div style=\"margin-top: 10px; padding: 10px; background: #dbeafe; border-radius: 6px;\"><strong>Why essential?</strong><br>• Heart must <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">relax</span> to fill with blood during <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">diastole</span><br>• Faster relaxation = better filling<br>• Maintains adequate <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">cardiac output</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700;\">Mechanism: The β₁-Adrenergic Pathway</div></div><div style=\"margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f0fdf4 0%, #dcfce7 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #059669; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 1: Adrenergic Stimulation</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">Catecholamines</span> released (epinephrine, norepinephrine)<br>• Bind <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">β₁-adrenergic receptors</span> on cardiac muscle cells<br>• Receptor activation begins cascade</div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #eff6ff 0%, #dbeafe 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #2563eb; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #2563eb; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 2: cAMP Production</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• β₁ receptor activates <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">adenylyl cyclase</span> enzyme<br>• Adenylyl cyclase converts <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">ATP → cAMP</span><br>• <span style=\"background: #dbeafe; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #1e3a5f;\">Intracellular [cAMP] increases</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #f3e8ff 0%, #e9d5ff 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 12px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 0.85rem; font-weight: 700; color: #7c3aed; margin-bottom: 8px;\">STEP 3: PKA Activation</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Increased cAMP activates <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">protein kinase A (PKA)</span><br>• PKA phosphorylates multiple target proteins<br>• Key target: <span style=\"background: #f3e8ff; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #6b21a8; font-weight: 600;\">Phospholamban</span></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #1e3a5f 0%, #2d4a6f 100%); color: #ffffff; padding: 14px 18px; border-radius: 12px; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1.05rem; font-weight: 700;\">The Critical Step: Phospholamban Phosphorylation</div></div><div style=\"display: grid; grid-template-columns: 1fr 1fr; gap: 14px; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef2f2 0%, #fee2e2 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #dc2626;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #991b1b; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Baseline State (No Stimulation)</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">Unphosphorylated phospholamban</span><br>• Phospholamban <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">inhibits SERCA pump</span><br>• SERCA = Sarcoplasmic Reticulum Ca²⁺-ATPase<br>• <span style=\"background: #fef2f2; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #7f1d1d;\">Slow Ca²⁺ reuptake into SR</span><br>• <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">Slower relaxation</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #dcfce7 0%, #bbf7d0 100%); padding: 14px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #059669;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #166534; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Stimulated State (β₁ Activation)</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• PKA <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">phosphorylates phospholamban</span><br>• Phosphorylation <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">reduces inhibitory effect</span><br>• SERCA pump now <span style=\"background: #f0fdf4; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #14532d; font-weight: 600;\">works more efficiently</span><br>• <span style=\"background: #dcfce7; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #166534;\">Fast Ca²⁺ reuptake into SR</span><br>• <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600; font-size: 1.05rem;\">FASTER RELAXATION</span></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fde68a 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #ca8a04; margin-bottom: 16px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Enhanced Calcium Reuptake Details</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><strong>What happens:</strong><br><div style=\"padding: 10px; background: white; border-radius: 6px; margin-top: 8px;\">1. <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">SERCA pump activity ↑</span><br>2. Ca²⁺ rapidly transported <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">back into SR</span><br>3. Cytoplasmic [Ca²⁺] <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">decreases faster</span><br>4. Ca²⁺ quickly dissociates from troponin C<br>5. Tropomyosin re-blocks myosin-binding sites<br>6. Cross-bridge cycling stops sooner<br>→ <span style=\"background: #fef3c7; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #78350f; font-weight: 600;\">Muscle relaxes more quickly!</span></div></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #e0e7ff 0%, #c7d2fe 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #4f46e5; margin-bottom: 14px;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #4338ca; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Result: Shortened Diastole</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\">• Rapid relaxation optimizes <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">diastolic duration</span><br>• Heart muscle relaxes <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">more quickly</span><br>• Chamber fills with blood <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">more effectively</span><br>• <span style=\"background: #e0e7ff; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; color: #3730a3;\">Ready for next contraction faster!</span></div></div><div style=\"background: linear-gradient(135deg, #fef3c7 0%, #fefce8 100%); padding: 16px; border-radius: 8px; border-left: 4px solid #ca8a04;\"><div style=\"font-size: 1rem; font-weight: 700; color: #92400e; margin-bottom: 10px;\">Clinical Significance</div><div style=\"font-size: 0.95rem; line-height: 1.6; color: #1e293b;\"><strong>Essential during stress or exercise:</strong><br><div style=\"padding: 10px; background: white; border-radius: 6px; margin-top: 8px; margin-bottom: 10px;\">• Heart rate <span style=\"color: #dc2626; font-weight: 600;\">increases ↑</span><br>• Less time available for diastole<br>• <span style=\"font-weight: 600;\">Faster relaxation crucial</span> for adequate filling<br>• Maintains cardiac output at high heart rates</div><div style=\"background: #fefce8; padding: 10px; border-radius: 6px;\"><strong style=\"color: #92400e;\">Positive Lusitropy ensures:</strong><br>✓ Heart can <span style=\"color: #059669; font-weight: 600;\">maintain higher heart rates</span><br>✓ Adequate filling even with <span style=\"color: #2563eb; font-weight: 600;\">shortened diastole</span><br>✓ Increased cardiac output during <span style=\"color: #7c3aed; font-weight: 600;\">stress/exercise</span></div></div></div>"
